I thought maybe I was a little hard on the magic system, that maybe if I read back through I'd be a little warmer to it. Maybe not.
The thing is, magic always has to follow rules. It just has to. How else are you supposed to explain what goes on in it? It can be explained, and still be magic. There are rules for the magic system.
- Magical talent is required.
The number of wizards in the world is very small.
- Spell power has to be learned through study or apprenticeship.
Magic never just "happens" for anyone. It's taught to them.
- You must use magic in a certain fashion to effect change.
The rules exist because magic is a powerful, and dangerous thing. It has to be explained why some people just can't use magic.
- One wizard can't cast spells with such power, so magical society had to develop "specialties" and limits so that each mage had power enough that they could be relied on to use it.
Those are the rules, yes. But at least most of those rules make SOME sense. I don't see why there needs to be a limit to how powerful you can get, or how many people can learn magic, or why there has to be boundaries of just who gets to learn which spells. They are rules, which are set up for no reason other than the author's desire and because it doesn't seem like the main character should know anything too fantastical.
You can't just say those rules don't make sense to someone who has never set foot on this particular fantasy planet. If it's hard for you to accept that those rules would make sense to everyone ELSE, it makes sense that these characters don't see why these rules are needed. It's just that simple.

I think that the book's magic is the weakness of the book. Without reading the sequels (I don't intend to), I can make a guess on what type of magic the other books will possess. The main reason for Sanderson's books to work is that he takes something that would typically be considered generic and/or stupid in other fantasy novels and twists them so that they become unique and smart.
Sanderson's main characters are all flawed and each of them have the potential to be the main villain. A few of them have personalities that drive the reader to distraction (in a good way), and many of them have tragic backstories. Even the main villain has a tragic backstory, and it's this backstory that causes people to side with the main villain. No one is good.
In his earlier series (also published by LDS), Sanderson has a character who has no magical ability whatsoever be forced into a role that they can never return from. She is made into a false hero. The magic system is simple and can even be reversed by a normal human (which actually makes the world less fantastical). Sanderson takes something that would typically annoy me in fantasy books (a world that is dominated by the "good" guys to the point that bad guys become the underdogs while doing very evil things), and he actually changes my mind. Why? Because he does it with a complex plot that is a mix of a lot of things that I like: political intrigue, backstabbing, betrayal, love that transcends, and many others. This story is about a bunch of horrible people who do not become better humans. Rather, they become even more horrible. Which is what makes an enemy a worthy one. All of Sanderson's main characters are enemies, friends, or villains, and they do not stay that way for very long (unless you're not willing to read the next story in the series).
Now, let's look at magic. I understand that the magic can only be done correctly for people who have taken enough wizard lessons, which I understand is basically Sanderson's way of saying that certain people are magical and can do magic, whereas certain other people cannot. And I understand that these people cannot "channel" magic, but that it is in their bones all the time. However, this magic does not make sense to me. The magic system could also be called a metaphor, as it seems to change based on what story and what part of the story it is used in. Sanderson's magic powers the plot. The magic does not just happen, even if it doesn't exist.
For example, in some stories, magic can be used to transport people. This is because the magic can affect some people's molecules or DNA. However, when that same magic is used in another novel, magic just happens and people cannot prevent it. They never question what is happening and just accept it, like they are a bunch of idiots.
In a story, the magic has an explanation, then it doesn't have an explanation. But then, later in that same story, it does have an explanation! The magic is a way to propel the plot but the problem is that there is never a logical explanation for how it works or why it works. For example, the magic in Mistborn can be used to make weapons out of metal (within the rules of the world) but the magic in Alcatraz can move a human being. Sanderson's magic system was not an afterthought but the actual propulsion of the plot. But if someone were to ask what happens to metals when they are transported by magic, he would not be able to answer.
This magic system is used primarily to show that the "good guys" are good and the "bad guys" are in fact, good. The magic also is used to prevent some of the characters from learning everything that is going on around them, and to let some of them stay blind to the truths that have revealed themselves to the other characters. This is what I do not like about the magic.
In the last book I will read today: Mistborn: The Hero of Ages.
What I like about it: A lot of heart, a lot of suspense, and a lot of good vs good. Also: very little magic.
What I did not like about it: Not nearly enough magic, a weird magic system, and too heavy on suspense. Also, for all that happened in it, most of it was really stupid.
The story is about a man who gets thrown into a magic world a hundred years after a bunch of magic and magic-type things happened. His goal: to survive, which is difficult considering that the bad guy is trying to capture him to get to the magic thing behind his back.
The first Mistborn book was a wonderful one, a simple story about a young man trying to take over a world with a few of his friends. The guy was pretty much a nobody, just an orphan who lived near the dump that the city built, and through this, was able to find allies who helped him with his goal.
This story was not the same. I was very disappointed. The main character lost most of his common sense, even though he was warned not to do it. He was also a little oblivious to stuff going on around him, although he did not act very stupid.
Every one of his enemies got stupid. The main villain took what seemed like a hundred years to get to him. They also made it seem like the main villain wanted to take everything that the main character worked for, and the main character was stupid enough to trust everything. If I were this main character, I would have at least trusted the guy a little.
The story was very, very suspenseful. The main thing I expected to happen happened, but the suspense was a way to make the world that the author made real and exciting. It was good for the book, like most of the story's strengths, but I really get tired of suspenseful stories that have no other heart to them.
